The design, optimization, and operation of complex physical systems and devices depends crucially our our ability to predicts their behavior. In application to chemical systems -- that is, those having behaviors that arise specifically from the molecular nature of matter --- prediction of behavior is often non-intuitive, and difficult to do reliably. Experiments play an important role in formulating our understanding of these system, and in providing data the can help with predictions at new conditions, but the vast number of possible chemical systems and thermodynamic states (e.g., temperature, pressure) and the sheer complexity of the behavior make it very diffcult to rely on experiment solely as the means to predict properties, and ultimately design and control complex systems.  Since the advent of quantum mechanics, a longstanding goal of scientists and engineers has been to predict thermophysical properties and behaviors from first principles, with little or no experimental input. The work performed with support from this grant has attempted to advance this goal.

Cluster-based methods in statistical mechanics express fluid properties in terms of power series in density or other state variables. Series coefficients can be determined rigorously from molecular models, and consequently these approaches can produce thermodynamic models that exactly describe the behavior that corresponds to the molecular model, over some range of conditions. This capability provides a unique route for connecting molecular-based treatments, including first-principles methods, to experiment, and in doing so it can guide the formulation of molecular models, methods, and theories; alternatively, this capability provides a modeling tool that can serve a wide range of applications in science and engineering. This project has advanced and applied these methods in several ways:

(1) we formulated a computer algorithm that greatly speeds up and simplifies the calculation of virial coefficients (a type of cluster integral) when applied to realistic molecular models; we also formulated algorithms to incorporate nuclear quantum effects in the calculations, which are important for low-mass molecules at low temperatures


(2) we tested and demonstrated the limits of cluster-series approach in describing the behavior of gases and gas mixtures. We also examined the approach in the context of condensation, the transformation that converts a gas to a liquid;


(3) we computed virial coefficients for a variety of simple molecular models, to help us understand the calculation and the application of the coefficients. These calculations have significantly exceeded what was previously considered possible;

(4) we formulated a new method for evaluating properties of materials by molecular simulation, one which takes an approximate theory as its starting point. As part of this project, we developed the approach with the cluster-series as a starting point, allowing for more rapid calculation of properties by molecular simulation;

(5) we computed very accurate and precise virial coefficients for helium from first-principles quantum mechanics, providing a description of its properties  in the gas phase that has less error than what can be obtained even with state-of-the-art experiments. We used these coefficients to compute the pressure-temperature-density relationship, and the speed of sound as a function of temperature and pressure. This capability is a foundational component of metrology, as helium is often used to calibrate experimental apparatus.






